It will not be / It will be not
by astaroth » Sat 08.08.2009 12:23 pm Hi,this time is about English. It's something bugging for quite some time but didn't find anyone to ask before I'm wondering whether saying something like it will be not (or with any other modal verb) is grammatically correct. At times it feels to me more appropriate than it will not be especially when I want to stress the not part. A real situation when I answered it will be not was something like this:last year while talking with my former advisor he asked whether a model would be reproducing a certain result and I answered "It will be not". The construct stumbled him a bit, but he is not a native speaker ...
